  "prompt_type": "affective",
  "prompt_text": "How would you help a person who has been betrayed by a close friend rebuild their ability to trust?",
  "response_text": "Rebuilding trust after a betrayal can be a challenging process, but it's not impossible. Here's a step-by-step guide to help your friend navigate this difficult situation:\n\n1. Acknowledge the pain: Encourage your friend to express their feelings about the betrayal. Let them know that it's okay to feel hurt, angry, and confused. Acknowledging their emotions can help them process them more effectively.\n\n2. Encourage self-reflection: Help your friend examine their beliefs about trust and relationships. Ask them to consider what they expect from friends, what signs they look for to determine trustworthiness, and how they can set boundaries to protect themselves in the future.\n\n3. Foster self-compassion: Remind your friend that they are not responsible for the actions of others and that it's important to be kind to themselves during this difficult time. Encourage them to practice self-care and engage in activities that bring them joy and comfort.\n\n4. Encourage forgiveness: While forgiveness doesn't mean forgetting or condoning the betrayal, it can help your friend move forward and heal. Help them understand that forgiveness is a process, and it's okay if it takes time.\n\n5. Set realistic expectations: Discuss with your friend the importance of setting realistic expectations for future relationships. Encourage them to be cautious but not overly suspicious, and to give people the benefit of the doubt when appropriate.\n\n6. Seek support: Encourage your friend to seek support from other trusted friends, family members, or a mental health professional if needed. Surrounding themselves with positive, supportive people can help them heal and rebuild their trust.\n\n7. Practice mindfulness: Suggest that your friend practice mindfulness techniques, such as meditation or deep breathing, to help them manage their emotions and stay present in the moment.\n\n8. Focus on the present: Encourage your friend to focus on the present and the people in their life who are trustworthy and reliable. Help them remember that not everyone will betray them, and there are still good people in the world.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 8\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 9\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 8\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
